data.text:
I realised that despite my website’s tagline, I haven’t done many genealogy posts. So, here’s one.

(Edit 4 Dec 2021: Barbados has abolished its monarchy.)

(Edit 9 Sep 2022: Her Majesty Queen Elizabeth II has passed away.)

Elizabeth II (21 April 1926 – 8 September 2022), full name Elizabeth Alexandra Mary Windsor (formerly Mountbatten), served as Head of the Commonwealth and Supreme Governor of the Church of England and reigned as Queen of the United Kingdom, Canada, Australia and New Zealand from 6 February 1952 until her death, as Queen of Pakistan from 6 February 1952 until 21 March 1956, as Queen of South Africa from 6 February 1952 until 31 May 1961, as Queen of Ceylon from 6 February 1952 until 22 May 1972, as Queen of Ghana from 6 March 1957 until 1 July 1960, as Queen of Nigeria from 1 October 1960 until 1 October 1963, as Queen of Sierra Leone from 27 April 1961 until 19 April 1971, as Queen of Tanganyika from 9 December 1961 until 9 December 1962, as Queen of Jamaica from 10 August 1962 until her death, as Queen of Trinidad and Tobago from 31 August 1962 until 1 August 1976, as Queen of Uganda from 9 October 1962 until 9 October 1963, as Queen of Kenya from 12 December 1963 until 12 December 1964, as Queen of Malawi from 9 July 1964 until 9 July 1966, as Queen of Malta from 21 September 1964 until 13 December 1974, as Queen of the Gambia from 18 February 1965 until 24 April 1970, as Queen of Rhodesia from 11 November 1965 until 2 March 1970, as Queen of Guyana from 26 May 1966 until 23 February 1970, as Queen of Barbados from 30 November 1966 until 30 November 2021, as Queen of Mauritius from 12 March 1968 until 12 March 1992, as Queen of Fiji from 10 October 1970 until 6 October 1987, as Queen of the Bahamas from 10 July 1973 until her death, as Queen of Grenada from 7 February 1974 until her death, as Queen of Papua New Guinea from 16 September 1975 until her death, as Queen of Solomon Islands from 7 July 1978 until her death, as Queen of Tuvalu from 1 October 1978 until her death, as Queen of Saint Lucia from 22 February 1979 until her death, as Queen of Saint Vincent and the Grenadines from 27 October 1979 until her death, as Queen of Belize from 21 September 1981 until her death, as Queen of Antigua and Barbuda from 1 November 1981 until her death, and as Queen of Saint Kitts and Nevis from 19 September 1983 until her death. She was previously the Duchess of Edinburgh by marriage from 20 November 1947 until 6 February 1952. She inherited the thrones after the death of her father George VI, and upon her own death was succeeded by her son Charles III. Her sister Princess Margaret Rose, Countess of Snowdon (21 August 1930 – 9 February 2002) was the Countess of Snowdon 6 October 1961 until her divorce on 11 July 1978 as the first wife of Antony Armstrong-Jones, 1st Earl of Snowdon. She was the mother of David Armstrong-Jones, 2nd Earl of Snowdon. The sisters were members of the House of Windsor, of which Elizabeth was head, a branch of the House of Wettin.
